title: For Trade:  Sig Sauer P245 (P220 Compact) .45 Auto, DA/SA, SRT, Night Sights
postcontent:
Up for grabs is a Sig Sauer P245, which is technically no longer in production. The P245 is a .45 auto compact and slightly shorter version of the P220. It was replaced by the P220 Compact, although nothing changed but the name. The P245 features a DA/SA trigger with a decocker and the Short Reset Trigger (SRT). It has an aluminum frame and stainless slide with a nitron finish.

This gun has some light holster wear. It was used as my carry and only very lightly fired. There have been about 500 rounds through the gun in the 9 years its been alive. I would rate it a 8/10. It comes with two 6-round magazines and the original factory night sights (Trijicon) that aren't nearly as bright as they used to be, but still have life in them. I do not have the original case. I will include a new(ish) Tactical Tailor pistol case with the right offer.

Sorry about my pics. Let me know if you'd like to see any specific photos of any of the internals. Truly, the only real wear is the holster wear you see towards the very end of the slide.

This is a single-stack .45 auto. The compact pistol is a "cut-down" variant of the famous SIG-Sauer P220, which is widely recognized as the most reliable pistol on the planet. Intended mostly for US market, this pistol is suitable for concealed carry and as a police backup weapon. The P245 has a traditional SIG-Sauer reliability, and, while somewhat heavy for a concealed gun, it offers a good recoil control. P245 was manufactured in Germany by the J. P. Sauer & Sohn company, which is a part of the international SIGARMS corporation.

The P245 is a short recoil operated, locked breech pistol. It uses a typical Browning-style cam operated barrel, which locks into the ejection window in the slide. The slide is made from stamped steel, and has a separate breechblock held within the slide by the cross-pin. The frame is made from aluminum. The trigger is double/single action and features the short reset trigger as well as an external hammer and a decocking lever on the left side of the frame. There's no manual safety, but P245 is provided with automatic firing pin safety. Just point and shoot.

Please be respectful and honest with your emails. You can expect the same from me. Thanks for looking. Happy Holidays.

title: For Sale:  Kimber Super Carry Pro .45ACP ***Used - Cheap***
postcontent:
NOTE:  Ridiculously low offers will be ignored.  Don't waste my time or yours.

Just bought this and function fired it...works perfectly. I have not shot it for accuracy. This is a Kimber Super Carry Pro. The Super Carry Line of 1911 pistols by Kimber are one of their top of the line guns. Series 70, rounded grip, full-size frame with 4" bushing-less barrel, match-grade everything, night sights (2011), nice trigger, ambi safety, etc. The pictures speak to the condition of this gun.

This one isn't cheap, but it is bargain-priced for what it is.

This gun shows plenty of honest, carry-type wear, mostly around the muzzle and on the right side. The right side safety has a nick in it but doesn't affect function in the slightest. If I have an extra right-side safety laying around I'll swap it out...no guarantees on that and don't count on it. It's dirty. I photo'd it while dirty just to show the unmolested condition of the gun. I'll give it a thorough cleaning prior to transfer. The bore is fine. I think it's been carried far more than it's been shot.

The sale will include the original box with all the paperwork, manual, one Kimber mag, one Wilson Combat mag (because I'm a really nice guy!) and two of the Kimber dis-assembly tools.

Transfer will be at Colorado Gun Broker in Bailey. It's easy to get to on Hwy 285 only 25 mins from the C-470/US 285 interchange and it's an easy drive...easier than driving across Denver.

Like I said...I'm letting this one go cheap. I know it's got some holster wear. So what. It's a gun that has an MSRP of $1596. They generally sell for around $1300 and up on GunBroker + shipping + transfer fees.

Seriously...I have the Ultra version and a Super Carry Custom HD version (full-size, all steel). Fantastic guns and I'd shoot them against any other brand with any ammo. I've sold thousands of Kimbers in the past and owned dozens. None have ever failed me and the Super Carry line is one of their best.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 31 12 GA Lightweight
postcontent:
This is a Remington Model 31 Lightweight shotgun, manufactured in 1948, 12 gauge and with a ventilated Poly-choke installed.  

The Remington 31 is prized for its smooth operation and is often sought out by Remington enthusiasts.  Of all the shotguns I have owned, (870, Mossberg 500, Winchester 1300) this is the smoothest of them all, hands down.

Remington 31's were issued to the FBI, LAPD and the US military during WWII.  

This shotgun is the lightweight version which has a receiver made from what Remington called "AEROMET" but is basically an aluminum alloy.  It makes it 1 pound lighter than the regular Model 31.   Originally it was a FULL choke barrel, but a ventilated Poly-Choke was installed at some point.  The Poly-choke has multiple settings.

This is a really nice shotgun and is great for a collector or someone who is looking for a good lightweight hard working shotgun.  

Face to face sale, Oregon ID required, bill of sale preferred.
